            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Ken Wright is a product of San Francisco\u2019s foggy western avenues. Born and raised in the Outer Richmond, he is the son of a Filipina immigrant mother and a white American father who left the picture before Ken\u2019s tenth birthday. This early departure solidified a quiet, profound bond between Ken and his mother, and instilled in him a deep-seated sense of responsibility. Growing up, the garage of their small duplex was his sanctuary, where he developed a fascination with the mechanical workings of cars, spending weekends tinkering with old engines.\n\nThis passion led him to City College of San Francisco, where he earned an Associate's degree in Automotive Technology. For nearly fifteen years, Ken worked as a mechanic, his hands perpetually stained with grease. He loved the logic of diagnostics and the satisfaction of a perfectly tuned engine. However, the physical toll began to wear on him. Aching knees and a chronically sore back made him reconsider his future. A fellow mechanic who had made the switch suggested he apply to Muni. It was the same system he loved, just from a different seat.\n\nThe transition from mechanic to operator was a turning point. At 36, he traded his wrench for the wheel of a 40-foot bus. The work was less physically demanding but required a new kind of mental fortitude. Now, at 49, he\u2019s a veteran operator, often navigating the city\u2019s busiest artery on the 38 Geary line. His daily routine starts before dawn, his commute a short ride on a colleague\u2019s bus to the depot. He is a silent observer of the city\u2019s pulse, watching its diverse occupants board and alight, each with their own story.\n\nDivorced for five years, Ken\u2019s life revolves around his work and his 17-year-old daughter, Maya, who lives with her mother in Daly City. He pours his overtime pay into a college fund for her, dreaming of her attending a UC school\u2014a future far beyond what he could have imagined for himself. His hopes are simple: see Maya thrive, retire with his pension in a decade, and maybe, finally, buy and restore that '68 Mustang he\u2019s always wanted. Ken Wright isn\u2019t just a resident of San Francisco; he is part of its essential rhythm, a steady hand guiding the city through its day."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was twelve. The old Datsun wouldn\u2019t turn over, and he saw the panic in his mother\u2019s eyes\u2014she\u2019d be late for her cleaning job. He popped the hood, the smell of oil familiar even then. His small hands traced the wires until he found it: a loose battery cable. He tightened it with pliers from the garage and the engine roared to life. The look of relief and pride on his mother\u2019s face wasn\u2019t just about the car; it was the moment he knew he could fix things for her.\n\n2.\nHe was 28, his hands permanently stained with grease. An old Mercedes with a fuel injection problem had stumped everyone at the shop for days. Ken stayed late, living inside the schematics, fueled by cheap coffee. The moment he finally heard the engine hum to a perfect, steady rhythm, a clean logic fell into place. It wasn't about the paycheck. It was the pure satisfaction of untangling a puzzle no one else could, of imposing order on mechanical chaos. That feeling was his masterpiece.\n\n3.\nThe breaking point came at 35, under a Ford F-150. He was on a creeper, and when he tried to push himself up, a blinding pain shot through his lower back, and his knee locked. He lay there for a full minute on the cold concrete, not just in pain, but in fear. He saw his future: a body broken by the work he loved. The cold realization hit him that his hands could fix any engine, but they couldn't fix himself. It was time for a change.\n\n4.\nMaya was fourteen, and her science teacher was talking about her potential, using words like \u2018biochemistry\u2019 and \u2018research.\u2019 Ken just sat there at the small desk, nodding, but inside, a fierce, overwhelming pride was building. He saw a future for her stretching far beyond his own garage or driver's seat. Driving back to Daly City, he pictured her on a UC campus. From that day on, every early morning and every overtime shift wasn't a burden; it was a down payment on her dream.\n\n5.\nHe was driving the 38 Geary on a foggy pre-dawn run. As he pulled away from a stop in the Richmond, he caught his own reflection in the rearview mirror, superimposed over the waking city. He saw the tired faces of cooks and nurses, the same determination he saw in his mother years ago. He wasn't just driving a bus; he was the steady pulse of the artery. He had traded the logic of a single engine for the complex, beautiful rhythm of the entire city."
